# Git staged and dirty worktree context handling

- When this repo already has staged, modified, or untracked files after context
  compaction or a resumed task, do not automatically call them "foreign" or
  unrelated.
- First inspect `git status`, staged diff, unstaged diff, and untracked file
  contents. Match each file to recent Qwertystock tasks, rules, deploy notes,
  or production fixes before deciding whether it belongs in the current commit.
- If a file is clearly a temporary artifact, editor scratch file, build output,
  dump, key, log, or unrelated generated data, leave it out and mention it.
- If staged files are safe and match the project context, preserve and commit
  them together with the related rule/code changes instead of dropping them.
- Never revert, reset, unstage, or overwrite existing work just because the
  current summarized context did not mention it. If the diff is unclear, read it
  and decide conservatively; ask only when it cannot be safely classified.
- Before pushing, verify that the commit does not include secrets, dumps,
  runtime caches, `node_modules`, built assets that should be generated, or
  one-off local scratch files.
